Q3: Difference between reshape and view in PyTorch

  1. view()
	 - Returns a new tensor that shares the same memory as the original tensor.
	 - Example:
		 x = torch.arange(6)
		 y = x.view(2, 3)
	 - Important:
		 - No memory copy
		 - Works only if tensor is contiguous in memory
		 - If not contiguous, view() will fail.

  2. reshape()
	 - More flexible than view().
	 - Example:
		 x = torch.arange(6)
		 y = x.reshape(2, 3)
	 - What happens internally:
		 - If possible, behaves like view()
		 - If needed, creates a copy of the tensor
		 - Always works, even when memory is not contiguous.

