Q5: Shared memory: torch.from_numpy()

  - If you create t = torch.from_numpy(n), t shares memory with the numpy array n.
  - If you modify n during training, t silently changes too — because torch.from_numpy() shares memory, it does NOT make a copy.
  - Your training data gets corrupted with no error message.
  - This is one of the nastiest bugs in ML pipelines because:
	  - No exception is raised
	  - No warning appears
	  - Model just trains on wrong data
	  - Results are subtly wrong
	  - You spend hours debugging the wrong thing
  - ❌ Dangerous — shares memory: t = torch.from_numpy(n)
  - ✅ Safe — creates a copy: t = torch.tensor(n)

